1
00:02:40,703 --> 00:02:45,416
- Honey... do you hear that?
- Hear what?

2
00:02:55,051 --> 00:02:56,553
Hey, Barbara?

3
00:03:04,102 --> 00:03:07,897
Did you hear that?
I could have sworn I heard whispering.

4
00:03:08,940 --> 00:03:11,609
You're reading my mind, that's all.

5
00:03:11,609 --> 00:03:14,445
My thoughts sound like whispers.

6
00:03:14,445 --> 00:03:17,866
Oh, yeah?
What were you thinking?

7
00:03:18,533 --> 00:03:20,076
I love you, Doc.

8
00:03:20,493 --> 00:03:24,706
You sure make it fun to wake up
before dawn, I'll tell you that.

9
00:04:43,534 --> 00:04:45,203
Frank?

10
00:04:47,163 --> 00:04:48,831
Hey, Frank?

11
00:05:00,718 --> 00:05:02,345
Hey, Frank.

12
00:05:02,845 --> 00:05:06,099
- Did you finish last night?
- No.

13
00:05:06,975 --> 00:05:09,936
Honey, it's a quarter to 6:00.

14
00:05:09,936 --> 00:05:11,813
It's important.

15
00:05:12,105 --> 00:05:14,190
Okay. Okay.

16
00:05:16,818 --> 00:05:18,486
Thanks.

17
00:05:30,623 --> 00:05:32,333
Okay.

18
00:05:32,583 --> 00:05:34,585
That's everything.

19
00:05:36,170 --> 00:05:37,755
Helium for the balloons!

20
00:05:37,922 --> 00:05:41,426
I'm picking up a tank at Harold's
right after I drop you off...

21
00:05:41,592 --> 00:05:43,219
per your instructions.

22
00:05:43,428 --> 00:05:46,514
Did I think Of that? Cool.

23
00:05:46,514 --> 00:05:49,726
I must be starting to get
this delegating authority stuff.

24
00:05:49,892 --> 00:05:54,105
Well, Mrs. Magoo, I guess
that's why they made you principal.

25
00:05:54,897 --> 00:05:56,774
I guess so.

26
00:05:58,109 --> 00:05:59,986
Honey, don't smoke.

27
00:05:59,986 --> 00:06:01,779
Hey, come on! Come on!
You're gonna make me crash.

28
00:06:02,655 --> 00:06:06,743
Look, I'll quit smoking when
you decide to get pregnant, all right?

29
00:06:17,211 --> 00:06:18,504
HEY, guys!

30
00:06:24,344 --> 00:06:26,637
- Hi!
- Hi.

31
00:06:33,269 --> 00:06:34,979
- Be very careful.
- Here I come.

32
00:06:35,146 --> 00:06:37,106
Watch your step.

33
00:06:42,612 --> 00:06:44,364
You all right?

34
00:06:46,199 --> 00:06:47,367
Hey, Jill!

35
00:06:49,243 --> 00:06:50,995
<i>- Hey.
- Hi.</i>

36
00:06:52,121 --> 00:06:53,956
- Who's the chef?
- Oliver.

37
00:06:54,123 --> 00:06:56,959
Oh, great, I love burnt hot dogs.

38
00:06:57,377 --> 00:06:59,420
Thanks.
So, when's Ben coming home?

39
00:06:59,420 --> 00:07:03,216
Six weeks, four days, and nine hours.

40
00:07:05,676 --> 00:07:06,969
Okay, now watch the edges.

41
00:07:06,969 --> 00:07:08,554
- Don't spill it.
- I got it.

42
00:07:08,721 --> 00:07:10,598
Let's take it over here.

43
00:07:10,598 --> 00:07:13,559
- Hey, Callie, how are you?
- Frank. Good. Good to see you.

44
00:07:13,726 --> 00:07:15,812
Hey, where's my helium?

45
00:07:15,812 --> 00:07:19,190
- Say you love me, baby.
- Not until you get me my helium.

46
00:07:19,357 --> 00:07:22,277
Righty-O.
I'll get right on it, dear.

47
00:07:24,654 --> 00:07:26,614
<i>-Oh You go here.
- Okay.</i>

48
00:07:26,781 --> 00:07:29,617
There's Jill.
I've got those receipts here.

49
00:07:30,368 --> 00:07:33,329
<i>- Hey, how you doing?
- How the hell are you?</i>

50
00:07:34,080 --> 00:07:36,999
- All right, bye.
- Bye. See you later.

51
00:07:48,302 --> 00:07:50,763
- Barbara!
- Hey, Frank!

52
00:07:52,765 --> 00:07:54,225
Good morning, Sam.

53
00:07:54,225 --> 00:07:58,020
And you must be Cindy.
It's nice to finally meet you.

54
00:07:59,772 --> 00:08:02,108
So, go in and take a look around?

55
00:08:03,443 --> 00:08:05,194
Yeah, you're both gonna
love this place.

56
00:08:21,961 --> 00:08:23,838
- Harold.
- Morning, Doc.

57
00:08:23,838 --> 00:08:26,340
- Frank.
- Hey, Doc, how the hell are you?

58
00:08:26,507 --> 00:08:28,718
Heading over to the school fair?

59
00:08:28,718 --> 00:08:31,721
Nah, I gotta go to Butler County today
and make my rounds at the hospital.

60
00:08:31,721 --> 00:08:34,390
Come on, you've got to try out
this muscle machine I made.

61
00:08:34,390 --> 00:08:35,683
Show everybody how strong you are.

62
00:08:36,434 --> 00:08:37,435
I don't know.

63
00:08:37,435 --> 00:08:40,188
I should probably just sit down in the
shade and watch you young guys do it.

64
00:08:44,275 --> 00:08:46,694
<i>- See you, tough guy.
- Right.</i>

65
00:08:53,784 --> 00:08:55,077
Okay. Thanks, Jill.

66
00:08:55,077 --> 00:08:56,913
We need finger paints.

67
00:08:56,913 --> 00:08:59,332
Okay. I'll get them.

68
00:09:00,500 --> 00:09:02,168
Just put it on the table.

69
00:09:16,307 --> 00:09:18,351
Finger paints. Okay.

70
00:09:27,276 --> 00:09:28,444
Yikes.

71
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:57,283
Whoa!

72
00:11:11,047 --> 00:11:13,591
Well, civilian pilot
spots the smoke.

73
00:11:13,883 --> 00:11:17,970
And then I get here and find two
of my officers passed out like babies.

74
00:11:17,970 --> 00:11:21,223
And everything on that side
of the white line is out cold.

75
00:11:21,515 --> 00:11:24,685
So somebody starts talking
about chemical weapons...

76
00:11:24,685 --> 00:11:28,814
and somebody hits a panic button,
and then you people are calling.

77
00:11:29,774 --> 00:11:32,568
<i>- There you go.
- Look, there is no research lab.</i>

78
00:11:32,568 --> 00:11:34,612
There is no chemical plant.

79
00:11:34,779 --> 00:11:38,658
There is no toxic waste dump.
There is no nuclear plant.

80
00:11:38,824 --> 00:11:41,994
- There's no nothing around here.
- Okay.

81
00:11:43,454 --> 00:11:44,705
Nothing on the news channels.

82
00:11:44,705 --> 00:11:46,999
Nothing on the news services.
Nobody's got it yet.

83
00:11:47,249 --> 00:11:48,876
Good.

84
00:11:50,503 --> 00:11:53,839
I'm just gonna take myself in there and
get a look-see.

85
00:12:03,641 --> 00:12:04,809
- Ed.
- Hey.

86
00:12:05,059 --> 00:12:07,978
- That's Frank McGowan's truck, right?
- What's left of it.

87
00:12:08,145 --> 00:12:11,482
- Lucky you wasn't in town today, Doc.
- What's going on here?

88
00:12:11,649 --> 00:12:14,694
Nobody knows nothin', not even
that fed doctor down there.

89
00:12:14,902 --> 00:12:18,823
She brought this whole circus
with her, and they ain't got a clue.

90
00:12:32,712 --> 00:12:36,215
Now, go on out there and see
what the hell's going on. Be careful.

91
00:12:36,382 --> 00:12:38,843
- Stay here?
- Yeah, we're just waiting.

92
00:12:39,009 --> 00:12:40,177
All right, good.

93
00:13:00,698 --> 00:13:01,490
Hey!

94
00:13:01,657 --> 00:13:04,118
Pull him back!
Get him out of there! Let's go!

95
00:13:04,452 --> 00:13:05,661
Come on! Come on!

96
00:13:07,455 --> 00:13:08,748
Get him down!

97
00:13:08,956 --> 00:13:10,875
- Stay back boys!
- Excuse me.

98
00:13:11,375 --> 00:13:13,502
Hits 'em like a hammer, Doc.
That's all we know.

99
00:13:13,669 --> 00:13:16,422
<i>- Some kind of chemical? Gas?
- No, it can't be.</i>

100
00:13:16,589 --> 00:13:19,592
The edges of the affected area
are well-defined.

101
00:13:20,301 --> 00:13:21,302
Stationary.

102
00:13:21,469 --> 00:13:26,432
- Doc, this is Dr. Susan...
- Verner. Like Turner, with a "V."

103
00:13:27,183 --> 00:13:29,769
Epidemiologist,
National Science Foundation.

104
00:13:29,769 --> 00:13:30,770
Alan Chaffee.

105
00:13:30,770 --> 00:13:31,854
- MD?
- Yeah.

106
00:13:32,021 --> 00:13:35,441
He's breathing. Good pulse.
I think he just fainted.

107
00:13:35,816 --> 00:13:37,776
Is Midwich affected by this?

108
00:13:37,777 --> 00:13:40,196
- My hunch would be, yes.
- My wife's in Midwich.

109
00:13:40,362 --> 00:13:42,323
We're trying to get through
for the last six hours, Doc.

110
00:13:42,323 --> 00:13:43,991
Nobody picks up the phone,
nobody calls out.

111
00:13:43,991 --> 00:13:47,411
Could somebody please get me
some blood and urine samples?

112
00:13:50,164 --> 00:13:52,666
- What's the call?
- 98.

113
00:13:54,001 --> 00:13:55,795
You going?
Okay, all right.

114
00:13:56,754 --> 00:13:59,298
Just take it easy.
Bring him a blanket.

115
00:14:18,943 --> 00:14:21,612
- You okay?
- Yeah.

116
00:14:56,438 --> 00:14:58,232
What happened?

117
00:15:25,009 --> 00:15:26,135
You okay?

118
00:16:02,880 --> 00:16:04,840
Barbara? Barbara?

119
00:16:05,633 --> 00:16:08,177
Thank God.
Are you all right?

120
00:16:10,095 --> 00:16:11,931
Sweetheart, are you okay?

121
00:16:12,264 --> 00:16:16,477
- I'm cold.
- All right, come on. Let's go home.

122
00:17:02,398 --> 00:17:05,234
Oh, no. Oh, no.

123
00:17:05,526 --> 00:17:06,902
Oh, no.

124
00:17:07,319 --> 00:17:08,612
<i>Heavenly Father...</i>

125
00:17:09,488 --> 00:17:12,408
we mourn these lives cut short...

126
00:17:12,992 --> 00:17:16,412
without warning or apparent purpose.

127
00:17:16,662 --> 00:17:20,499
We search for a reason and find none.

128
00:17:21,583 --> 00:17:25,295
We have become accustomed
to the power of science...

129
00:17:25,295 --> 00:17:29,550
so when we were struck down, we
turned to science and asked, "Why?"

130
00:17:30,551 --> 00:17:32,845
But it could not answer.

131
00:17:33,053 --> 00:17:35,639
So now we turn our eyes
toward Heaven...

132
00:17:35,639 --> 00:17:39,852
and seek our comfort
in God's infinite mercy.

133
00:17:41,353 --> 00:17:43,105
Let us pray.

134
00:17:43,814 --> 00:17:46,650
Our Father, who art in Heaven...

135
00:17:46,650 --> 00:17:48,652
...hallowed be Thy name...

136
00:17:48,652 --> 00:17:51,572
Thy kingdom come,
Thy will be clone,

137
00:17:51,572 --> 00:17:53,991
on Earth as it is in Heaven.

138
00:17:54,158 --> 00:17:56,994
Give us this day our daily bread,

139
00:17:57,202 --> 00:17:59,496
and forgive us our trespasses,

140
00:17:59,496 --> 00:18:02,666
as we forgive those
who trespass against us,

141
00:18:02,916 --> 00:18:07,296
and lead us not into temptation,
but deliver us from evil.

142
00:18:07,296 --> 00:18:10,257
For Thine is the kingdom,
and the power,

143
00:18:10,257 --> 00:18:13,260
and the glory, forever and ever.

144
00:18:13,260 --> 00:18:14,470
Amen.

145
00:18:56,220 --> 00:18:59,640
- Did you ever hear of Charles Fort?
- Huh-uh.

146
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:01,433
<i>He wrote The Book of the Damned,</i>

147
00:19:01,433 --> 00:19:03,310
about things that nobody's
been able to explain.

148
00:19:03,310 --> 00:19:07,606
Like frogs falling from the sky,
blue snow, red rain...

149
00:19:07,773 --> 00:19:09,691
Are you suggesting I read him?

150
00:19:09,691 --> 00:19:11,568
No. No. It's just that...

151
00:19:12,152 --> 00:19:15,572
Sometimes mysteries don't get solved.

152
00:19:15,572 --> 00:19:18,575
I mean, look, what if something
like this happens again?

153
00:19:18,575 --> 00:19:21,161
I don't know. What do I do?
Can I call you?

154
00:19:21,161 --> 00:19:24,039
Well, of course, you can call me.

155
00:19:24,039 --> 00:19:28,085
Oh, and by the way, I suggest
you read Sir Arthur Conan Doyle.

156
00:19:28,085 --> 00:19:30,337
Sherlock Holmes once said,

157
00:19:30,504 --> 00:19:32,131
"When you've eliminated
the impossible,

158
00:19:32,131 --> 00:19:34,842
whatever remains,
however improbable,

159
00:19:35,008 --> 00:19:37,136
must be the truth."

160
00:20:00,075 --> 00:20:02,327
It's not possible.

161
00:20:02,786 --> 00:20:05,956
You made a mistake.
Do it again.

162
00:20:07,207 --> 00:20:10,127
Well, I mean, I don't have a problem
running the tests again, Callie.

163
00:20:10,335 --> 00:20:12,588
I have felt like this before
in the morning.

164
00:20:12,588 --> 00:20:14,840
It is just some kind of bug.

165
00:20:31,857 --> 00:20:33,525
Melanie?

166
00:20:46,830 --> 00:20:48,707
Melanie?

167
00:20:48,999 --> 00:20:50,542
What's the matter?

168
00:20:55,255 --> 00:20:59,885
- Maybe I can help.
- No. You can't.

169
00:21:05,390 --> 00:21:06,808
- There they are!
- Hey, you guys!

170
00:21:06,975 --> 00:21:09,478
We're empty!
We need some more here!

171
00:21:09,686 --> 00:21:12,064
Hi, how are you?

172
00:21:12,064 --> 00:21:13,398
It's good to see you.

173
00:21:13,565 --> 00:21:14,775
Hi.

174
00:21:16,193 --> 00:21:17,152
Wow!

175
00:21:17,903 --> 00:21:19,321
Wow!

176
00:21:21,740 --> 00:21:24,451
Hey, Ben, this is fantastic.

177
00:21:34,294 --> 00:21:36,964
Callie, look up and smile.

178
00:21:44,179 --> 00:21:46,265
So, Ben, after a year in Japan,

179
00:21:46,431 --> 00:21:49,768
did you ever think you'd have
to get used to being a dad?

180
00:22:00,529 --> 00:22:02,572
She's pregnant again.

181
00:22:08,870 --> 00:22:10,747
Hello, Doc.

182
00:22:13,041 --> 00:22:14,960
I said, "Hello."

183
00:22:16,461 --> 00:22:18,547
How long have you been
standing there?

184
00:22:18,547 --> 00:22:21,216
- Oh, ages.
- Liar.

185
00:22:24,261 --> 00:22:26,221
Big boy.

186
00:22:30,017 --> 00:22:31,143
Hey.

187
00:22:32,019 --> 00:22:33,687
Why are you kissing me like that?

188
00:22:35,480 --> 00:22:39,318
I wanted to know first,
so I used a home pregnancy kit.

189
00:22:39,651 --> 00:22:42,321
Yeah, well, honey, you know,
those are unreliable.

190
00:22:42,487 --> 00:22:46,241
And that's why I went to see
Dr. Cornright just to make sure.

191
00:22:46,450 --> 00:22:48,577
Gonna open it?

192
00:22:56,835 --> 00:22:58,628
Alan?

193
00:23:08,138 --> 00:23:09,723
Hi. You got a minute?

194
00:23:09,723 --> 00:23:11,767
Sure.

195
00:23:24,488 --> 00:23:26,281
Well, everything's positive.

196
00:23:27,199 --> 00:23:29,242
You are pregnant.

197
00:23:34,706 --> 00:23:37,167
We'd been trying, you know.

198
00:23:38,001 --> 00:23:40,003
Look. Umm...

199
00:23:40,337 --> 00:23:43,340
I wanted to tell you something before
you hear it from somebody else.

200
00:23:44,883 --> 00:23:46,760
There's a lot of pregnancies.

201
00:23:46,760 --> 00:23:49,012
I mean, a lot.

202
00:23:49,513 --> 00:23:53,558
Much more than would
normally be expected.

203
00:23:54,351 --> 00:23:56,520
What do you mean?

204
00:23:58,313 --> 00:24:00,148
Well, umm...

205
00:24:00,649 --> 00:24:02,818
Is something wrong with my baby?

206
00:24:03,151 --> 00:24:05,946
No, no, no, no,
it's nothing to indicate that.

207
00:24:05,946 --> 00:24:07,656
I mean, you're a normal,
healthy young woman...

208
00:24:07,656 --> 00:24:10,200
Alan, don't talk to me like a doctor.

209
00:24:11,785 --> 00:24:13,537
Okay.

210
00:24:14,413 --> 00:24:18,875
All the pregnancies seem to date
from the clay of the blackout.

211
00:24:18,875 --> 00:24:20,419
Oh, no!

212
00:24:32,639 --> 00:24:34,391
Dr. Susan Verner
has flown in...

213
00:24:34,558 --> 00:24:37,144
This is all because
of that blackout, ain't it?

214
00:24:38,437 --> 00:24:40,772
Why don't you just come out
and say something!

215
00:24:40,772 --> 00:24:42,315
They don't know that for sure.

216
00:24:42,315 --> 00:24:44,651
They are all gonna be deformed!

217
00:24:44,651 --> 00:24:46,361
For everyone's sake...

218
00:24:47,821 --> 00:24:49,906
Wait a minute.
That's not true.

219
00:24:49,906 --> 00:24:53,493
Excuse me! That's not true.
There's no reason to believe that.

220
00:24:53,493 --> 00:24:56,496
Barbara and I are pregnant. Okay?
We know how you feel.

221
00:24:56,496 --> 00:24:59,791
We know what a lot of you are
thinking, so let me say right now

222
00:24:59,791 --> 00:25:02,335
the same thing I've told
a lot of you individually.

223
00:25:02,335 --> 00:25:05,338
The standard tests have not
revealed one abnormality.

224
00:25:05,338 --> 00:25:08,216
Anywhere. Not one. All right?

225
00:25:08,216 --> 00:25:11,428
Let's listen... Just a minute.
Let's listen to Dr. Verner, please.

226
00:25:11,428 --> 00:25:12,512
She's come to talk to us.

227
00:25:12,512 --> 00:25:15,724
Dr. Susan Verner,
ladies and gentlemen.

228
00:25:17,767 --> 00:25:19,144
I wanna start off by saying

229
00:25:19,144 --> 00:25:22,105
that we are all very concerned
about your well-being.

230
00:25:22,105 --> 00:25:24,441
- Sure.
- Yeah.

231
00:25:24,441 --> 00:25:27,611
But ultimately it will come down
to individual decisions.

232
00:25:28,445 --> 00:25:32,491
And I understand that these decisions
will be probably the most intimate,

233
00:25:32,657 --> 00:25:37,245
personal, difficult decisions
that you ever make in your life.

234
00:25:37,537 --> 00:25:39,706
However, because your pregnancies

235
00:25:39,706 --> 00:25:42,375
have attracted intense
scientific interest,

236
00:25:42,375 --> 00:25:44,711
including
the National Institutes of Health

237
00:25:44,711 --> 00:25:46,213
and National Science Foundation,

238
00:25:46,213 --> 00:25:50,008
those of you who decide
to have your child

239
00:25:50,008 --> 00:25:52,427
will have all prenatal expenses paid.

240
00:25:52,636 --> 00:25:56,598
You'll also receive $3,000 monthly
as an allowance.

241
00:25:58,934 --> 00:26:01,728
If you allow your child to be examined

242
00:26:01,728 --> 00:26:04,189
and tested
on some sort of regular basis.

243
00:26:04,189 --> 00:26:07,526
Is that $3,000 a family?

244
00:26:07,526 --> 00:26:09,903
What if your wife and your daughter
both have kids?

245
00:26:10,570 --> 00:26:12,739
Then, you would receive $6,000.

246
00:26:14,032 --> 00:26:16,618
$6,000?

247
00:26:19,120 --> 00:26:24,417
Look, I don't want you to interpret this
allowance as some sort of a pressure.

248
00:26:24,834 --> 00:26:26,586
It isn't. It's your decision.

249
00:26:26,586 --> 00:26:29,506
And if you decide to terminate,

250
00:26:29,506 --> 00:26:32,551
then, of course,
you have the right to do that.

251
00:26:32,551 --> 00:26:34,344
And you can do it privately.

252
00:26:34,511 --> 00:26:38,098
Or if financially unable, a medical
